                {
                    "title": "<span style=\"font-size:26px;\">Key points</span>",
                    "content": "<ul class=\"key-points\">\n<li>Worldwide, the most visible digital divide is the one between women and men, with 58.3% of men and 48.4% of women using the Internet in 2019.</li>\n<li>In regions with a high Internet use penetration, including developed regions and countries in Latin America and the Caribbean, there was only a small difference in Internet usage between women and men (at or below 2%).</li>\n<li>In relative terms, the gender gap among Internet users has grown wider in developing regions, increasing from 15.8% in 2013 to 22.8% in 2019. The largest gap was observed in Central and Southern Asia (51.3%).</li>\n<li>Globally, women are less likely than men to own a mobile phone, with men\u2019s ownership being 6.8 percentage points higher than women\u2019s, on average.</li>\n</ul>\n",
                    "contentActions": [],
                    "creaDate": 1602471192292,
                    "pubDate": 1602471192292,
                    "status": "PUBLISHED",
                    "media": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "image": {
                            "url": "https://www.arcgis.com/sharing/rest/content/items/d6a2f8291c9c4b60a80431f65cf104af/resources/michael-demoya-rL1TdmPa5u8-unsplash__1602471051953__w1200.jpg",
