                },
                {
                    "title": "<span style=\"font-size:28px;\">The most visible digital divide is the one between women and men</span>",
                    "content": "<p>Beyond development status, there are additional digital divides, such as by level of education, skills and geographical location (including urban versus rural), but the most visible is the digital divide by sex. In many places, women have less access to technology and hence use it less than men.</p>\n<p>In 2019, 58.3% of men were using the Internet, against only 48.4% of women (see figure I), resulting in a difference of 10 percentage points. In developed countries, there was a small gender gap, with 87.6% of men and 85.6% of women were using the Internet. In developing countries, there was a significant difference between men using the Internet (52.8%) and women (40.7%). Furthermore, the difference in levels of access to the Internet between men (24.4%) and women (13.9%) in the least developed countries was significant.</p>\n<p>A similar picture emerges from a regional perspective. In regions with a high Internet use penetration, including Australia and New Zealand, Northern America and Europe and Latin America and the Caribbean, there were only small differences in usage between men and women. In other regions, however, the gaps were substantial, with the exception of Oceania (excluding Australia and New Zealand) where Internet use was low overall.</p>\n",
                    "contentActions": [
                        {
                            "id": "MJ-ACTION-1598609631920",
                            "type": "navigate",
                            "index": 8
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "MJ-ACTION-1598609642799",
                            "type": "navigate",
                            "index": 8
                        },
                        {
